<div class="post-date">Oct 27</div>
<h2><a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?id=775" title="David Wiesner &#8211; The Art"> David Wiesner &#8211; The Art</a></h2>

<div class="entry">


     

  	<p><a href="http://www.houghtonmifflinbooks.com/authors/wiesner/home.html">David Wiesner &#8211; The Art of Visual Storytelling.</a></p>

	<p>With my sister-in-law Janie visiting, the topic turns to children&#8217;s books. She&#8217;s worked libraries and enjoys a good kids book. When she visited the library her first stop was the childrens&#8217; room where she grabbed a book for Darlene to read.</p>

	<p>When I work down there one night a week I try to sneak a read of a picture book or two. My favorites are without a doubt by David Wiesner (whom I know is also a favorite of a few of my friends).</p>

	<p>&#8220;Tuesday&#8221; is wonderful and well deserved its Caldecot Award. However, ranking right up there is his 1999 &#8220;Sector 7&#8221; which snagged a Caldecot Honor that year.</p>

	<p>Inspired, I searched the web and was psyched to find his book publisher has posted a very nice website.  They include enlargements of several of his drawings and an excellent article about the &#8220;creative process&#8221; behind &#8220;Tuesday&#8221; from the rough concepts and storyboards to his research and final paintings.</p>

	<p>Definitely worth a visit.</p>



 
<div class="line"></div>

<div class="smallcat">Posted in <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?c=Culture">Culture</a></div>
<div class="smalluser"> by <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?author=E.G.+Yarnetsky">E.G. Yarnetsky</a></div>
